 Resumo
 The Opta win probability favours an Aston Villa win at
 50.5%, while there are decent chances of a draw at 31.6%. A
 Brighton win seems unlikely, but not impossible, at 17.9%.
 Emery will likely be the happier of the two managers at the
 break, but he will know that anything but a win tonight
 could effectively end Villa’s slim hopes of challenging for
 the title - especially with Manchester City already up to a
 3-0 lead against Fulham. Hurzeler, meanwhile, will be
 content with the way his side have defended, but will be
 desperate to see better service into the likes of Mitoma,
 Welbeck, Gross and Gomez.

 Resumo
 The first half comes to a close here at Villa Park as Aston
 Villa and Brighton go into the break locked in a stalemate.
 Neither side has particularly been at their best tonight,
 though both came close towards the end of the half. Buendia
 saw a low drive whistle past the outside of the post with
 Verbruggen rooted to the spot, while Welbeck failed to beat
 Martinez with plenty of space and time moments later. There
 has been little to write home about from either side beyond
 those chances, though Hurzeler did opt for an early
 substitution as Baleba was shown a yellow card inside the
 opening two minutes, which allowed Milner to come on to a
 warm reception and equal Gareth Barry’s all-time Premier
 League appearance record. Villa edge the xG battle at the
 break, though its marginal and not particularly impressive
 from either side, with the hosts generating 0.47 xG to
 Brighton’s 0.07 xG.

